body:
Consider the following code ([playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=a1d6f83220a9c91511d51868bb4a05ae)):

```rust
pub struct Loader<'a> {
    location: &'a str,
}

impl<'a> Loader<'a> {
    pub fn new<S: AsRef<str>>(location: &'a S) -> Self {
        Self { location: location.as_ref() }
    }
}

fn main() {
    let x = Loader::new("hello world");
    println!("{}", x.location);
}
```

The compiler gives
```
error[E0277]: the size for values of type `str` cannot be known at compilation time
  --> src/main.rs:12:25
   |
6  |     pub fn new<S: AsRef<str>>(location: &'a S) -> Self {
   |            --- - required by this bound in `Loader::<'a>::new`
...
12 |     let x = Loader::new("hello world");
   |                         ^^^^^^^^^^^^^ doesn't have a size known at compile-time
   |
   = help: the trait `std::marker::Sized` is not implemented for `str`
   = note: to learn more, visit <https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/ch19-04-advanced-types.html#dynamically-sized-types-and-the-sized-trait>
```

It would be better to suggest adding an `S: AsRef<str> + ?Sized` bound to the `new` function. Ideally it would only show that message if `?Sized` would cause the function to compile, but that's just gravy.

cc @XAMPPRocky
